Approaches to learning: a data analysis

Aim of the chapter and data

This chapter explores the impact of various factors on learning outcomes. To achieve this aim a survey was conducted among statistics course students in 2014. The researchers collected information about gender and age of the participants. The survey asked the participants to indicate their attitude towards statistics, and fill in the questionnaire describing their learning habits. The answers were divided into three categories, describing general ways of learning. They were defined as deep, surface and strategic learning. Finally, the final mark of the course, given in points, was included in the data. After initial processing of the data, I have produced a data set, consisting of 166 observations over 7 variables.

learning2014 <- read.table("Z:\\Documents\\RProjects\\IODS-project\\data\\learning2014.csv", header = TRUE, sep = ",", row.names = 1)

Summary statistics

As you can see from the graph below, female participants comprise the majority of the course. They tended to be only slightly younger than their male counterparts, and slightly more successful in the final grading. As for leaning habits, both male and female students show similar affiliation with deep and strategic learning, whereas surface learning is markedly more preset within the male population. Another notable difference between genders can be seen in attitude, with male students expressing higher regard for statistics than female students.

In our further analysis we plan to investigate the impact on learning outcomes, that is, we are treating our points variable as dependent variable. Our analysis of the correlation between different variables indicates that attitude has the strongest and most statistically significant relationship to points. Less significant, but still of interest, is potential positive association of the course mark with strategic learning (stra) and negative one with surface learning (surf). These relationships make common sense: positive attitude towards the study subject and strategic approach to learning result in higher marks, while surface learning allows very limited understanding of the subject and will probably lead to a lower grade. In the next section we will introduce some tests to these assumptions.

Linear regression analysis and model validation

Our first attempt at fitting the linear model has demonstrated that only attitude has a statistically significant association with the grade of the course. Although beta coefficients of strategic and surface learning are higher, their low t-values and high p-values, do not allow us to interpret them as significant enough. As the R2 value suggests,the current model explains around 19% of our records.

model_learning2014 <- lm(points~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)

For the next step we have excluded surface learning from the equation. Overall, it did not significantly change our initial results. It shows very similar results for our attitude variable, and the statistical significance of strategic learning has increased only to the 0.1 level.

We can conclude that attitude towards statistics and strategic learning to some extent are positively associated with the final grade. In other words, positive attitude towards the study subject and strategizing the learning process increase chances to complete the course successfully.

To make sure that the second model is the best one, we are going to compare their AIC values. Indeed, we can observe that the model with only two variables attitude and strategic learning (stra) has the lowest AIC index, so it is a better fit.

library(AICcmodavg)

models <- list(model_learning2014, model2_learning2014)
mod.names <- c("att.stra.surf", "att.stra")
aictab(cand.set = models, modnames = mod.names)

Finally, we are going to test the validity of our model. Our constant variance assumption is tested with residuals vs fitted values plot. Since we can observe no questionable patterns, we can conclude that the assumption is valid. We test normality assumption with a QQ-plot, which suggests that the errors are reasonably distributed. Our Residuals vs Leverage plot shows that no value has a significant leverage. As you can see the scale of the leverage axis, the highest value is estimated to be only around 0.05.

Selecting possible factors and formulating a hypothesis

My first assumption is that high consumption of alcohol(high_use) would be visible in teens school performance, i.e.in grades (G3) and class failures, as well as their absences from school. I also speculate that difficult relationship with family may lead to alcohol abuse (famrel, evaluated by respondents on the scale from 0 to 5). Moreover, I assume that teenagers from urban districts might consume much more alcohol than their counterparts from rural areas, due to easier access to bars, clubs and parties (address). Finally, I will consider the impact of gender (coded here as sex).

As you can see from two summaries below, there is no dramatic differences between teens consuming high amounts of alcohol from urban and rural addresses is not very great, so I am not going to consider it at modelling stage. Meanwhile, comparison by gender does reveal some notable differences. The proportion of boys, consuming high amounts of alcohol is significantly larger, and they tend to have lower grades. Boxplot B also makes clear that higher mean of absences among girls is driven by outliers, and mean is actually higher for boys. Family relationship does not show variation by gender, but it tends to be lower among teens, who have high alcohol consumption.

library(tidyr)

alc$address <- alc$address %>% as.factor()
alc$sex <- alc$sex %>% as.factor()

alc %>% group_by(address, high_use) %>%  summarise(count = n(), mean_grade = mean(G3), failures = mean(failures), absences = mean(absences), famrel = mean(famrel))

The Model

To get a model, that could detect teenagers with high values of alcohol use I am going to create four logistic models with different combinations of variables, I discussed above, as predictors. Then, I am going to test, which model has the lowest AIC value, i.e.is a better fitting one. The table below shows that the best model (m2) includes failures, absences, sex and famrel.

Summary of the model reveals that all regression coefficients are statistically significant. The most significant relationship is with absences and sex. Estimated regression coefficient for absences is 0.09, which means that the estimated increase in log odds of having high_use as TRUE is 0.08 for each increase of 1 in the absences, whereas sex coefficient should be interpreted as the log odds of having high_use as TRUE for boys is 1.05 higher than for girls.

Next, I am calculating odds ratios from regression coefficients. The resulting values should be interpreted as follows:

  • for a one unit increase in failures the odds of having high_use as TRUE increase by 77%.
  • for a one unit increase in absences the odds of having high_use as TRUE increase by 9%.
  • for boys the the odds of having high_use as TRUE increase by 185%.
  • for a one unit increase in famrel the odds of having high_use as TRUE decrease by 26%.

None of the confidence intervals contain 1, which means that all variables are not independent from high_use.

m1 <- glm(high_use ~ failures + absences + sex + G3 + famrel, data = alc, family = "binomial")

m2 <- glm(high_use ~ failures + absences + sex + famrel, data = alc, family = "binomial")

m3 <- glm(high_use ~ failures + absences + sex, data = alc, family = "binomial")

m4 <- glm(high_use ~ famrel + absences + sex, data = alc, family = "binomial")

library(AICcmodavg)

models <- list(m1, m2, m3, m4)
mod.names <- c("fal.abs.sex.gr.fam", "fal.abs.sex.fam","fal.abs.sex", "abs.sex.fam" )

Predictive power of my model

Now I will test how well does my model predict the high values of alcohol consumption among teenagers. As can be seen from the tabulations below, this model predicts 17% of the cases wrongly. The overall accuracy of the model is rather high (the mean prediction error is only 0.25).

probabilities <- predict(m2, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   244   15
##    TRUE     77   34
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)  %>% prop.table() %>% addmargins()
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE        Sum
##    FALSE 0.65945946 0.04054054 0.70000000
##    TRUE  0.20810811 0.09189189 0.30000000
##    Sum   0.86756757 0.13243243 1.00000000
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2486486

Applying clustering methods to Boston data set

Overview of the data

For this task I am using Housing Values in Suburbs of Boston, which is included into MASS package. The data set consists of 506 observations and 14 variables. See more information about the data here.

Summary of the variables reveals a few striking characteristics of Bostos suburbs. Per capita crime rate crim shows that majority of suburbs have relatively low crime rate with a few outliers. The measure black reveals that majority of suburbs has similar proportions of black population but there is a group of suburbs with very amount of black residents.

Correlation plots reveals that crime rate is strongly associated with accessibility of radial highways, rad, with full value property tax rate tax. These variables also highly dependent from each other. Relatively strong negative relationships are visible with distances to employment centers (dis), proportion of black residents (black), and median value of owner-occupied homes (medv). Suburbs with high grime rates also seem to located near industrial centers (indus) and,prbably as a result, be more polluted (nox).

Creating crime rate target variable

In order conduct lda analysis with crime rate as a target variable, I will need to transform it to a categorical data. I am going to create categories based on quantiles, but as the summary of this variable has indicated earlier, I am expecting to see a significant break in the third quantile.

# creating a quantile vector
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)

# creating a categorical variable 'crime'
values <- c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high")
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, label = values, include.lowest = TRUE)

# removing original crim from the dataset
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

# adding the new categorical value to scaled data
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

summary(boston_scaled$crime)
##      low  med_low med_high     high 
##      127      126      126      127

Dividing to train and test sets

Finally, I am dividing the set, allocating 80% as train data, and the rest as test data.

# number of rows in the Boston data set 
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)

# selecting randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

# train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

# test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

# saving the correct classes from test data
correct_classes <- test$crime

# removing the crime variable from test data
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

LDA analysis

Fitting the model

Now the data set is ready to be fitted to LDA with crime rate as the target variable. The result is visualized with a biplot. It is clear from the plot that my initial hypothesis was correct, the cases are divided in two distinct clusters: a bigger one, consisting of all low and med_low cases, majority of med_high and a smaller one with majority of high cases and several med_high. Arrows make it clear that the strongest factor dividing the clusters seems to be accessibility of radial highways, rad.

lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plotting the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1.5)

Testing the model

Test of the models prediction capacity has revealed that it is rather accurate. It has correctly predicted all high cases, 78% of med_high and 68% of low. The model seems performs worse in the med_low category with only 41% of correct predictions.

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

km <-kmeans(Boston_scaled, centers = 4)

pairs(Boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

I will determine the oprimal number of clusters by plotting total of within cluster sum of squares by number of cluster (with maximum k = 10). We can see that the first elbow of the plot at k=2. Running k-means algorithm with two centers indeed gives a clear picture of two clusters.

set.seed(123)

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(Boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

# k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(Boston_scaled, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

Dimensionality reduction techniques

Principal Component Analysis

Overview of the data

I am going to use the method of Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on a data set, I have constructed from Human Development Index data and Gender Inequality Index data. The purpose of this exercise is to reduce the dimensions of the resulting data set, in other words, compress the varibles into a smaller number of components, that we could then attempt to interpret.

This data set consists of 155 countries and 8 variables. The summary of the variables suggest, that global development is imbalanced (shoker!). For instance, we can see drastic differences between means ans medians in maternal mortality ratio (Mat.Mor) and adolescent birth rate (Ado.Birth), that suggests that there is a group of countries with very high values, pushing the mean up. Correlation plot suggests that there is a significant positive relationship between these valuables. Furthemore, the two variables have strong negative relationships with life expectancy (Life.Exp), education expectancy (Edu.Exp) and the ratio of female and male secondary education expectancy (Edu2.FM).

Also can be of interest a dramatic rise from min to 1st quantile in Edu2.FM, and the ration of participation in the labor market (Labo.FM).

Interpretation

PCA on not-standardized data shows that GNI as a variable with the highest variance is enough to predict the overall variance of the data set.

When the data set is scaled, the variance of each variable is 1, and we can see that principal components has become more multifaceted. The second biplot demonstrates that:

  • PC1 of a country is pulled to positive values by adolescent birth rate and maternal mortality ratio. It is pulled to negative values by GNI, life expectancy at birth, expectancy of education and secondary education ratio between women and men.

  • PC2 of a country is pulled to positive values by womens labour force participation rate and proportion of women in parliament.

Overall, PC1 could be regarded as womens quality of life index, PC2 - as womens societal integration index.

MCA

To demonstrate how MCA is used and interpreted I am going to select 8 variables from tea data set. We are going to see how the choice of the product, modes of tea consumption and circumstances of drinking it (meals of the day) are related to each other.

Examination of MCA plot reveals some interesting patterns:

  • Green tea consumption seems to occur during dinner time, while consumption of black tea and Earl Grey seems to be rather independent from meals of the day.

  • People who prefer packaged tea tend to shop in chain store markets, whereas those who prefer unpackaged at tea shops.

  • Earl Grey is often consumed with sugar, while black tea for many goes well with lemon.

# selecting columns
keep_columns <- c("Tea", "How", "how", "sugar", "where", "lunch", "breakfast", "dinner")

tea_time <- dplyr::select(tea, one_of(keep_columns))

# multiple correspondence analysis
mca <- MCA(tea_time, graph = FALSE)

Impact of nutrition on growth

Overview of the data

The first technique summary measure approach is going to be tested on RATS data set (see Crowder & Hand 1990). The data set records weights of three groups of rats on different diets over the period of 64 days.

# structure of the data set
glimpse(RATSL)
## Rows: 176
## Columns: 5

cat_vars2 <- c("ID", "Group")

Graphical display of growth

To start with, lets investigate plots of growth profiles by group. According to Figure 1.1, all diets seem to result in growth of rats body mass, however, group 1 demonstrates a more moderate trend than the other two.

# drawing the plot
ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = day, y = weights, linetype = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:8, times=2)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(RATSL$weights), max(RATSL$weights))) + labs(y = "Weight (gm)", x = "Time (days)", title = "Figure 1.1", subtitle = "Growth profiles of individual rats by group")

Lets standardize weights to observe tracking, a tendency for subjects with higher values to have higher values throughout the study. Figure 1.2 shows that growth trend for some rats is reversed, and overall, now growth trends appear less dramatic.

# standardizing weights
RATSL <- RATSL %>% group_by(day) %>%
  mutate(std_weights = scale(weights) )  %>%
  ungroup()

# drawing new plot
ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = day, y = std_weights, linetype = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:8, times=2)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(RATSL$std_weights), max(RATSL$std_weights))) + labs(y = "Standardised Weight", x = "Time (days)", title = "Figure 1.2", subtitle = "Standardised growth profiles of individual rats by group")

By plotting the means of the three groups, it is possible to observe that the groups appear to have distinct profiles. Although group 2 and 3 seem very close, they do not overlap.

# extracting number of days measurements were made
n <- RATSL$day %>% unique() %>% length()

# summary data with mean and standard error of weights by group and day 
RATSS <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Group, day) %>%
  summarise( mean = mean(weights), se = sd(weights)/sqrt(n) ) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Group'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(RATSS, aes(x = day, y = mean, linetype = Group, shape = Group)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = c(1,2,3)) +
  geom_point(size=3) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(1,2,3)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-se, ymax=mean+se, linetype="1"), width=0.3) +
  theme(legend.position = "right") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(weight) +/- se(weight)") + labs(x = "Time (days)", title = "Figure 1.3", subtitle = "Mean response profiles for three diets")

Summary measure analysis

Summary measure analysis implies exploring the difference between groups on the basis of a single value, which captures some important characteristic of each group. This technique is commonly used as a preliminary stage for longitudinal data analysis. For the purposes of this exercise I am going to use the mean as a summary measure.

Boxplots of mean profiles (Figure 1.4) indicate that groups seem to be different. Group 1 has the least variability. Meanwhile, group 2 and 3 seem somewhat skewed into the opposite directions. The groups have no outliers.

# draw boxplots for groups
ggplot(RATSS, aes(x = Group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", geom = "point", shape=23, size=3, fill = "white") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(weight), days 1-64") +
  labs(title = "Figure 1.4", subtitle = "Mean response profiles for three diets")
## Warning: `fun.y` is deprecated. Use `fun` instead.

One-way analysis of variance (ANOVA)

In order to confirm that the diets indeed have a different impact on growth, I am going to conduct one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) on the means. The resulting p value is smaller than 0.05, thus, we can conclude that groups 2 and 3 differ significantly from group 1. Next, I am performing a post hoc test (Tuckey test), to be sure that all groups also differ from each other. As p values of the test suggest, it is indeed so.

# fitting anova
ratss_aov <- aov(mean ~  Group, data = RATSS)
summary(ratss_aov)

# post-hoc test
TukeyHSD(ratss_aov)

Assuming independence

Before testing linear mixed effect modelling, I am going to wrongly (!) assume that the measurements are independent from each other and fit a multiple linear regression model. In other words, I treat the data set as if there are 360 observations from different people. Ignoring within-subject dependencies leads to higher standard error estimates for the week regression coefficient. In this case it is 0.2524.

# fit model assuming independence
bprs_m0 <- lm(bprs ~ week + treatment, data = BPRSL)
summary(bprs_m0)

Linear mixed effects models

Now I am going to demonsterate more appropriate models for repeated measurements data.

First, I am fitting a mixed effect model with random intercept. By allowing the intercept to be different we can account for difference between subjects. Immediately we can observe that standard error for week is considerably lower only 0.1503.

Regression coefficient for treatment has a very low t-value, which suggests that that the null hypothesis might be true, and there is no difference between the two groups.

Nevertheless, I am going to do another fit with random intercept and random slope. This model allows duration of treatment to have an effect on the slope. Again, t-value for treatment is close to 0.

Next, we are going to allow interaction between treatment and time. In this case too, the result appears to suggest that the treatment does not have a different effect on BPRS.

In addition to model summaries, I present results of their comparisons with ANOVA. The random intercept and random slope model (bprs_m2) has the lowest AIC and chi squared values, so it should be considered a better fit.

# fit model with random intercept
bprs_m1 <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + (1|id), data = BPRSL, REML = FALSE)
